{{refimprove|date=March 2017}} In [[espionage]], agents under '''non-official cover''' ('''NOC''') are operatives who assume [[Covert operation|covert]] roles in organizations without official ties to the government for which they work.
This is in contrast to an agent with [[official cover]], where they assume a position in their government, such as the [[diplomat|diplomatic service]], which provides them with [[diplomatic immunity]] if their espionage activities are discovered. Agents under non-official cover do not have this "safety net", and if captured and [[Espionage#Law|charged as spies]] are subject to severe criminal punishments, up to and including [[execution]]. Agents under non-official cover are also usually trained to deny any connection with their government, thus preserving [[plausible deniability]], but also denying them any hope of diplomatic legal assistance - or official acknowledgment of their service. Such agents or operatives may be referred to as a ''NOC'' (pronounced {{IPAc-en|n|ɒ|k}} {{respell|NOK}}).<ref>{{cite news | last = Shannon | first = Elaine | title = Spies for the New Disorder | work = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date = February 20, 1995 | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,982540-1,00.html | subscription = yes | accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref> or as "illegals" (see [[Clandestine HUMINT operational techniques#Stations under non-official cover|Clandestine HUMINT operational techniques]]). Sometimes, entire [[front companies]] or [[Strawperson|strawman]] entities are established in order to provide false identities for agents.
==History== An agent sent to spy on a foreign country might, for instance, work as a businessperson, a worker for a non-profit organization (such as a humanitarian group), or an academic. For example, the [[CIA]]'s [[Ishmael Jones]] spent nearly two decades as a NOC.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2008/sep/07/baring-bureaucratic-hurdles-at-cia/ |title= Tripping Over CIA's Bureaucratic Hurdles |author=John Weisman |work=Washington Times |date=September 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref>
Many of the agents memorialized without names or dates of service on the [[CIA Memorial Wall]] are assumed to have been killed or executed in a foreign country while serving as NOC agents. In nations with established and well-developed spy agencies, the majority of captured non-native NOC agents have, however, historically been repatriated through [[prisoner exchange]]s for other captured NOCs as a form of [[gentlemen's agreement]].
Some countries have regulations regarding the use of non-official cover: the CIA, for example, has at times been prohibited from disguising agents as members of certain aid organizations, or as members of the [[clergy]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
The degree of sophistication put into non-official cover stories varies considerably. Sometimes, an agent will simply be appointed to a position in a well-established company which can provide the appropriate opportunities.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} Other times, entire [[front organisation|front companies]] can be established in order to provide false identities for agents.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
Examples include [[Air America (airline)|Air America]], used by the CIA during the Vietnam War, and [[Brewster Jennings & Associates]], used by the CIA in [[Weapons of mass destruction|WMD]] investigations and made public as a result of the [[Plame affair]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
The journalist [[Udo Ulfkotte]] made a statement, referring to his past career at the German newspaper ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'', that he worked as a NOC for the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yp-Wh77wt1o |title=Dr Udo Ulfkotte, journalist and author, on RT |date=September 29, 2014}}</ref>
==Examples== Former MI6 officer "Nicholas Anderson" wrote an account of his service in a fictionalized autobiography (as per British law) entitled ''NOC: Non-Official Cover: British Secret Operations'', and two sequels: ''NOC Twice: More UK Non-Official Cover Operations'' and ''NOC Three Times: Knock-On Effect (Last of the Trilogy)''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Kind of Traitor: an interview with former MI6 intelligence officer Nicholas Anderson|url=http://www.historyextra.com/period/modern/our-kind-of-traitor-an-interview-with-former-mi6-intelligence-officer-nicholas-anderson/|website=historyextra.com|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=February 21, 2018|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref>
[[Michael Ross (Mossad officer)|Michael Ross]], a former [[Mossad]] officer, operated as a Mossad NOC or "combatant" as described in his memoir, ''The Volunteer: The Incredible True Story of an Israeli Spy on the Trail of International Terrorists'' (Skyhorse Publishing, September 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-60239-132-1}}).
Fictional examples include [[Chuck Barris]] who made a satirical claim to have been a NOC with 33 kills in his book and movie ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]''. Other examples are featured in the books ''[[Debt of Honor]]'', [[Ted Bell]]'s ''Pirate'', and ''[[The Eleventh Commandment (novel)|The Eleventh Commandment]]''; in the movies ''[[Mission: Impossible (film)|Mission: Impossible]]'', ''[[Spy Game]]'', ''[[The Bourne Identity (2002 film)|The Bourne Identity]]'', ''[[Safe House (2012 film)|Safe House]]'', and ''[[The Recruit]]''; and the TV shows ''[[The Americans (2013 TV series)|The Americans]]'', ''[[Burn Notice]]'', ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'', ''[[Covert Affairs]]'' and ''[[Patriot_(TV_series)|Patriot]]''.
