'''Sir Ralph Gore, 2nd Baronet''' (died 1661)<ref name = thePeerage/> was an [[Anglo-Irish]] politician, soldier and baronet.

He was the eldest son of [[Sir Paul Gore, 1st Baronet]] and Isabella Wycliffe, daughter of Francis Wycliffe.<ref name = thePeerage>{{cite web | url= http://www.thepeerage.com/p1965.htm#i19650 | title= ThePeerage - Sir Ralph Gore, 2nd Bt | accessdate= 8 January 2009}}</ref> Gore succeeded his father as baronet in 1629.<ref name = Burke/> He was [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) in the [[Irish House of Commons]] for [[Donegal County (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Donegal County]] from 1639 until 1648.<ref name = thePeerage/> In the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]], he was appointed colonel of 500 men by [[King Charles I of England]] to end the riots.<ref>{{cite book | last = Lodge | first = John | editor = Mervyn Archdall | title = The Peerage of Ireland or A Genealogical History of the Present Nobility of that Kingdom | volume = vol. III | location = Dublin | publisher = James Moore | year = 1789 | pages = 281–282 }}</ref>

On 23 April 1639, he married Anne Caulfeild, second daughter of the [[William Caulfeild, 2nd Baron Caulfeild of Charlemont|2nd Baron Caulfeild of Charlemont]].<ref name = thePeerage/> Gore was succeeded in the baronetcy by his only son [[Sir William Gore, 3rd Baronet|William]].<ref name = Burke>{{cite book | last = Burke | first = John | title = A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire | publisher = Henry Colburn and Richard Bentley | location = London | volume = vol. I | edition = 4th | year = 1832 | pages = 527 }}</ref>

